# Security Review: `app.js`

I reviewed `/tmp/p15-test-q3vdYp/app.js` (22 lines). The file is a minimal Express app with `/health` and `/users` endpoints. There are no user inputs processed, so classic injection (SQLi/XSS/command injection) is not currently exploitable, but there are still several meaningful security gaps. Findings are ordered by severity.

---

## 1. Broken Access Control — `/users` exposes PII without auth (OWASP A01:2021) — HIGH

`GET /users` returns names and email addresses to any caller. Even though the data is currently hardcoded, the endpoint sets an expectation that user records (PII) are public.

```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }, // PII, unauthenticated
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Require authentication and limit fields returned to the caller.

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.headers.authorization || '';
  const [, token] = header.split(' ');
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return non-sensitive fields by default
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name })));
});
```

---

## 2. Missing Security Headers (OWASP A05:2021 Security Misconfiguration) — HIGH

No `helmet` middleware, so the app ships without `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, CSP, etc.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
app.disable('x-powered-by'); // also removes "Express" fingerprint
```

---

## 3. No Rate Limiting (OWASP A04:2021 Insecure Design) — HIGH

Both endpoints can be hit unboundedly — trivial DoS and, once auth is added, brute-force risk.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));
```

Apply stricter limits on auth endpoints when they're added.

---

## 4. No CORS Policy — MEDIUM

Without an explicit CORS config, either nothing is set (blocking legitimate browser clients) or a dev teammate will later add `cors()` with no options, which defaults to `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`.

**Recommendation:** define an explicit allowlist.

```js
const cors = require('cors');
const allowed = (process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS || '').split(',').filter(Boolean);
app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, cb) => {
    if (!origin || allowed.includes(origin)) return cb(null, true);
    cb(new Error('Not allowed by CORS'));
  },
  credentials: true,
}));
```

---

## 5. No HTTPS / no `trust proxy` (OWASP A02:2021) — MEDIUM

`app.listen(3000)` binds plain HTTP. If deployed behind a TLS-terminating proxy, `req.ip`, `req.secure`, and rate-limit keys will be wrong without `trust proxy`.

**Recommendation:**

```js
app.set('trust proxy', 1); // trust first proxy (nginx/ALB/CloudFront)

// Redirect to HTTPS when not already secure
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' && !req.secure) {
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.headers.host}${req.url}`);
  }
  next();
});
```

Terminate TLS at the load balancer, or use `https.createServer` with valid certs.

---

## 6. No Centralized Error Handler — stack traces may leak (OWASP A05) — MEDIUM

There's no `app.use((err, req, res, next) => ...)`. Unhandled errors fall to Express's default handler, which leaks stack traces when `NODE_ENV !== 'production'`.

**Recommendation:**

```js
// 404
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' }));

// Error handler — always last
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err); // send to real logger in prod
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Internal Error' : err.message,
  });
});
```

---

## 7. No Request Body Limits — MEDIUM (forward-looking)

As soon as `express.json()` / `express.urlencoded()` is added, the default 100 KB is usually fine, but it should be explicit and small for JSON APIs.

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

## 8. Insufficient Logging & Monitoring (OWASP A09:2021) — MEDIUM

The only log statement is the startup message. Requests, auth failures, and errors are invisible.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const pino = require('pino');
const pinoHttp = require('pino-http');
const logger = pino({ redact: ['req.headers.authorization', 'req.headers.cookie'] });
app.use(pinoHttp({ logger }));
```

Redact secrets and cookies; ship logs off-box.

---

## 9. Hardcoded Port & Config — LOW

`app.listen(3000, ...)` should come from env so prod/test/dev differ cleanly. Also, `app.listen` runs at `require` time because `module.exports = app` is paired with `listen` in the same module — tests importing `app` will bind the port.

**Recommendation:** separate app from server.

```js
// app.js
module.exports = app;

// server.js
const app = require('./app');
const port = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
app.listen(port, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${port}`));
```

This also lets you import `app` into Supertest-based security tests without side effects.

---

## 10. `/health` is Unauthenticated and Timestamped — LOW

Exposing `new Date().toISOString()` is harmless, but `/health` returning rich internal state (DB status, commit SHA, etc.) in future iterations would leak recon data. Keep the public health check boring:

```js
app.get('/health', (_req, res) => res.status(200).send('ok'));
// Put deep health (DB, dependencies) on a separate, auth-gated or internal-only path
app.get('/health/deep', requireInternalOnly, deepHealthHandler);
```

---

## Items That Are NOT Issues (Explicitly Checked)

- **SQL / NoSQL injection**: no DB calls.
- **Command injection**: no `child_process`, `exec`, `eval`.
- **Path traversal / SSRF**: no filesystem or outbound HTTP.
- **XSS**: no HTML rendering; JSON responses with static data.
- **Prototype pollution**: no user-controlled object merging.
- **Deserialization**: no `JSON.parse` on untrusted input, no `node-serialize`.

---

